&lt;s&gt;You can&#39;t declaration variable second time&lt;/s&gt;. 

Deleting the second `let` will solve your problem.

```
function exerciseFour(value){
  let greaterThanFive = false;

  if (value &gt; 5) {
     greaterThanFive = true; // &lt;--- Remove `let` here.
  }

  return greaterThanFive;
}

function exerciseFive(name){
  let isSondra = false;

  if (name === &#39;Sondra&#39;) {
     isSondra = true;
  }

  return isSondra;
}

console.log(exerciseFour(3));
console.log(exerciseFour(7));
console.log(exerciseFive(&quot;Matt&quot;));
console.log(exerciseFive(&quot;Sondra&quot;));
```

The `let` keyword defines a new variable within the _lexical scope_. The lexical scope in the case of this line:

```
function exerciseFour(value){
  let greaterThanFive = false;   // &lt;----
  // ...
}
```

...is the function. The second `let` then _shadows_ the first variable, meaning a nested lexical scope has a variable with the same name but completely detached from the original. Its scope is the if statement block:

```
function exerciseFour(value){
  let greaterThanFive = false; // &lt;-- scoped to function
  if (value &gt; 5) {
    let greaterThanFive = true;  // &lt;-- define new variable, scoped to if statement
  }

  return greaterThanFive;
}
```

Therefore, once we _leave_ the scope of that if statement block, `greaterThanFive` references the _function-scoped_ variable, which is why it still has the value `false`.

Simply removing the second `let` will cause the statement to be an _assignment_ statement rather than a _variable declaration_:

```
function exerciseFour(value){
  let greaterThanFive = false;
  if (value &gt; 5) {
    greaterThanFive = true; // Assigns a new value to the variable
  }

  return greaterThanFive;
}
```

